        <div class="he-tell-card">
          <div class="he-tell-head">
            <span class="he-tell-num">01</span>
            <span class="he-tell-title">Menu length</span>
          </div>
          <p class="he-tell-body"><strong>8–15 mains</strong> = focused kitchen, confident in what it does. <strong>30+ items across four pages</strong> = volume operation. The freezer is doing most of the work; only the bestsellers will be great.</p>
          <div class="he-tell-tip">
            <span class="he-tell-tip-label">Order tip</span>
            Short menu? Trust the chef and pick what catches your eye. Long menu? Order the dish the place is <em>named for</em> — that's the one they can't afford to miss.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="he-tell-card">
          <div class="he-tell-head">
            <span class="he-tell-num">02</span>
            <span class="he-tell-title">Sourcing callouts</span>
          </div>
          <p class="he-tell-body">"<strong>Tajima wagyu</strong>," "<strong>Frog Hollow peaches</strong>," "<strong>Monterey Bay halibut</strong>" = the kitchen pays attention and can defend the price. Generic "<em>fresh fish</em>," "<em>premium beef</em>," "<em>house-made</em>" = they don't.</p>
          <div class="he-tell-tip">
            <span class="he-tell-tip-label">Order tip</span>
            The dish that drops a name is the dish to order. They wouldn't print the supplier if they couldn't back it up.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="he-tell-card">
          <div class="he-tell-head">
            <span class="he-tell-num">03</span>
            <span class="he-tell-title">How specials show up</span>
          </div>
          <p class="he-tell-body"><strong>Chalkboard, handwritten card, or verbal-only</strong> = real specials, changing nightly with what came in the door. <strong>Glossy printed insert</strong> that's been there a month? That's marketing dressed as specials.</p>
          <div class="he-tell-tip">
            <span class="he-tell-tip-label">Order tip</span>
            Real specials are where the freshest, most seasonal stuff lands. Always ask: <em>"What's actually special tonight?"</em>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="he-tell-card">
          <div class="he-tell-head">
            <span class="he-tell-num">04</span>
            <span class="he-tell-title">Description length</span>
          </div>
          <p class="he-tell-body">"<strong>Cacio e pepe — $24</strong>" trusts you to know what it is. A <strong>six-line description</strong> with adjectives stacked three-deep is selling, not feeding.</p>
          <div class="he-tell-tip">
            <span class="he-tell-tip-label">Order tip</span>
            Short, plain descriptions = signature dishes the kitchen is proud of. Long flowery ones = "<em>please believe this will be good.</em>"
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="he-tell-card">
          <div class="he-tell-head">
            <span class="he-tell-num">05</span>
            <span class="he-tell-title">The cheapest main</span>
          </div>
          <p class="he-tell-body">The cheapest entrée is the menu's <strong>honesty check</strong>. Creative, interesting, something you'd actually order? The kitchen has range top to bottom. A <strong>defensive Caesar with grilled chicken</strong>? They're playing it safe.</p>
          <div class="he-tell-tip">
            <span class="he-tell-tip-label">Order tip</span>
            If the entry-level main is dull, build dinner from the apps and sides — that's usually where the kitchen is having more fun anyway.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="he-tell-card">
          <div class="he-tell-head">
            <span class="he-tell-num">06</span>
            <span class="he-tell-title">The dish that doesn't fit</span>
          </div>
          <p class="he-tell-body">One Korean spot has <strong>bucatini</strong>. One Italian trattoria has <strong>bibimbap</strong>. That's a dish the chef brought from somewhere else they cooked for a long time — they're not putting it on the menu unless they nailed it.</p>
          <div class="he-tell-tip">
            <span class="he-tell-tip-label">Order tip</span>
            The "<em>wait, why is THAT on the menu?</em>" dish is almost always a chef's pet. Order it and ask about it — you'll get the story too.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="he-tells-foot">Six tells, every menu, no app required. <strong>Green Light reads with you</strong> — but once you can read the menu yourself, dinner gets a lot easier.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="he-glossary" aria-label="Menu words decoded">
      <p class="he-glossary-label">field guide</p>
      <h2 class="he-glossary-heading">Menu words, demystified.</h2>
      <p class="he-glossary-sub">A short cheat sheet to the terms that quietly do the work on a menu. Skim before you sit down — useful even when Green Light isn't open.</p>

      <div class="he-glossary-grid">
        <div class="he-gloss-card">
          <div class="he-gloss-head">
            <span class="he-gloss-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇯🇵</span>
            <span class="he-gloss-cuisine">Japanese</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="he-gloss-list">
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">omakase</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">"I leave it to you." No menu — the chef picks every course. Usually pricier, almost always worth it if the place is good.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">izakaya</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Japanese pub. Lots of small shared plates designed to keep pace with drinks — think tapas, but with skewers and karaage.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">donburi</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Anything served over a bowl of rice. Gyudon = beef. Oyakodon = chicken + egg. Cheap, fast, satisfying.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">robata</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Flame-grilled skewers and vegetables, charred over binchotan. Smoky, simple, ingredient-forward.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="he-gloss-card">
          <div class="he-gloss-head">
            <span class="he-gloss-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇰🇷</span>
            <span class="he-gloss-cuisine">Korean</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="he-gloss-list">
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">banchan</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">The half-dozen little side dishes that arrive free with your meal — kimchi, pickled radish, marinated spinach. Refills usually free too.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">jjigae</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Stew, served bubbling in a stone pot. Kimchi jjigae, sundubu jjigae (soft tofu), doenjang jjigae (fermented soybean).</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">bulgogi</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Thin-sliced beef in a soy-pear-sesame marinade, grilled or pan-cooked. The sweet, accessible gateway to Korean BBQ.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">ssam</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Means "wrapped." Grilled meat tucked into lettuce or perilla leaves with garlic, ssamjang paste, rice. Eat with hands.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="he-gloss-card">
          <div class="he-gloss-head">
            <span class="he-gloss-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇹🇭</span>
            <span class="he-gloss-cuisine">Thai</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="he-gloss-list">
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">gaeng</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Curry. Red, green, yellow, massaman, panang — each one is a gaeng with a different paste base. Heat varies wildly.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">yam</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Thai-style salad — punchy with lime, fish sauce, chili, herbs. Yam woon sen = glass noodle. Yam nua = grilled beef.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">pad</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">"Stir-fried." Pad thai, pad see ew (wide noodles, soy), pad krapao (basil + chili). Always wok-charred.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">larb</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Minced meat salad with toasted rice powder, lime, fish sauce, chili, mint. Northeastern (Isaan) staple, ferociously bright.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="he-gloss-card">
          <div class="he-gloss-head">
            <span class="he-gloss-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇲🇽</span>
            <span class="he-gloss-cuisine">Mexican</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="he-gloss-list">
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">mole</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">A slow-cooked sauce stacked with chilies, seeds, spices, and sometimes chocolate. Mole negro is the classic — complex, not sweet.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">al pastor</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Pork shaved off a vertical spit, marinated in chili and citrus, kissed with pineapple. Lebanese shawarma's Mexican cousin.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">antojito</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">"Little craving." Street snacks — sopes, tlacoyos, elote, esquites. Often the most fun part of any menu.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">aguachile</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Raw shrimp drowned in chili-lime juice. Faster, hotter, and greener than ceviche — usually served immediately.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="he-gloss-card">
          <div class="he-gloss-head">
            <span class="he-gloss-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇮🇹</span>
            <span class="he-gloss-cuisine">Italian</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="he-gloss-list">
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">primo / secondo</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">First course (pasta, risotto, soup) and second (the protein). Italian menus are sectioned this way — you can order either or both.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">antipasti</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Starters before the pasta — cured meats, cheeses, marinated vegetables, bruschetta. Designed for sharing.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">agrodolce</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">"Sour-sweet." A vinegar-and-sugar reduction glazed over meat, fish, or vegetables. Sicilian roots, vivid on the tongue.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">cacio e pepe</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Three ingredients: pasta water, Pecorino, black pepper. Looks plain on a menu, slaps you when it lands. Order it.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="he-gloss-card">
          <div class="he-gloss-head">
            <span class="he-gloss-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇮🇳</span>
            <span class="he-gloss-cuisine">Indian</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="he-gloss-list">
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">biryani</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Layered rice cooked with marinated meat, saffron, fried onions, and whole spices. Each region has its own — Hyderabadi is the famous one.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">masala</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Spice blend, not a single thing. Garam masala is the warm finishing one. Tikka masala = grilled, then in a creamy tomato sauce.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">saag / palak</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Both mean greens. Palak is specifically spinach; saag can include mustard, fenugreek, and other leaves blended down.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="he-gloss-row">
              <span class="he-gloss-term">thali</span>
              <span class="he-gloss-def">Sampler platter — several small curries, rice, breads, chutneys, dal, dessert. The best way to taste a kitchen's whole hand.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="he-glossary-foot">Six cuisines worth of <strong>menu-fluency</strong> in 30 seconds. The next unfamiliar dish you spot might already be on this list.</p>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
